  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q({a_p}_*(K|X^p))         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K).       \tag{5.1.12.2}       ]]></fr:tex>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2102</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.1.12</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the constant simplicial space associated to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_\bullet \colon  X_\bullet \to  S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> the morphism defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>.
    For an abelian sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, we can identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> with a cosimplicial sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> ((IV) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />).
    For a complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is the degree <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> component of the restriction of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_q]]></fr:tex>, then the components of the simple complex associated to the double complex defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K]]></fr:tex> are

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2084</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.12.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         (\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K)^n         = \bigoplus _{p+q=n} {a_q}_* K^{pq}.       \tag{5.1.12.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    
    The spectral sequence defined by the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.9.3" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K]]></fr:tex> can be written as

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2085</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.12.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q({a_p}_*(K|X^p))         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K).       \tag{5.1.12.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2103</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2.3</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We can show (by example, using (III) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />) that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> always admits resolutions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> on the right such that
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^r(X_q,K^{p,q})       =0       \quad \text {for } p,q\geqslant 0 \text { and } r>0.     ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is such a resolution, then we canonically have that

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2104</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )         \simeq  \operatorname {H}^n(\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)).       \tag{5.2.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    It is easy to show directly that the right-hand side is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>;
    for what follows, we are free to <fr:em>define</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex> by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    We can further show that the spectral sequence of the complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)]]></fr:tex>, filtered by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.9.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" /> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>)

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2105</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,F^p)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )       \tag{5.2.3.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.1.1" />).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2106</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2.7</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Combined with <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.5.xml" number="5.2.5" /> and specialised to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>, this equation proves <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    In concrete terms, this implies that, to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex>, we can proceed in two steps:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        We take a resolution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\xrightarrow {\sim } K']]></fr:tex> such that the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K']]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i {a_p}_*(F^p)=0]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>0]]></fr:tex>.
        The complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K'\in \mathrm {D}^+(S_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> (the derived category of the category of cosimplicial abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>) can be identified with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*K]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} a_*K]]></fr:tex> is the simple complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex> associated to the double complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{a_\bullet }_*K']]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
            <fr:p>The spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.2" /> generalises to a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2107</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.7.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.7.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \mathrm {R}^q{a_p}_*(K|X_p)         \Rightarrow  \mathrm {R}^{p+q}a_*K       \tag{5.2.7.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    induced by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" />.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
</fr:tree>
